    Given a cluster of ellipses (created with EllipsesIntoClusters) order the ellipses into an asymmetric grid. In an asymmetric grid each row is offset by 1/2 the horizontal spacing between. This forms a sawtooth pattern vertically.

    Note that the returned grid is 'sparse'. every other node is skipped implicitly. This is caused by the asymmetry. Each row is offset by one circle/grid element.

    Examples:
 3x6 grid will have 9 elements total.
 grid(0,0) = [0]
 grid(0,2) = [1]
 grid(0,4) = [2]
 grid(1,1) = [3]
 grid(1,3) = [4]
 grid(1,5) = [5]

    See Grid for a description of how the output grids are described. It uses a sparse format.

    See DetectCircleAsymmetricGrid for an example of an asymmetric grid
